<div id="main_content">
	<h2>College of Education's Hynes Wins Pegasus Professor Award</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">April 13, 2005</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 261px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE453/en_US/050413hynesmain.jpg" height="196" width="261"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>President John Hitt (left) presents the Pegasus Professor Award, which recognizes outstanding teaching, research and service, to Professor Michael Hynes of the College of Education.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=00240041338a60010331bcbbf6007e6f">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://edcollege.ucf.edu">UCF College of Education</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041338a60010331bcbbf6007e05&amp;mode=news">UCF Honors Outstanding Faculty, Students at Founders' Day</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041338a60010331bcbbf6007e23&amp;mode=news">UCF Names 14 Professors Emeriti</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Michael Hynes' many contributions to improving math and science education include a new academy to help train teachers, dozens of research projects and the mentoring of hundreds of professors and college students.</font></span></p>
<p><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">Hynes, who was named UCF's 2005 Pegasus Professor Award winner on Wednesday, also makes a more direct impact on math education at his </span><city></city>
<place></place>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Oviedo</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> home.</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&quot;He has personally helped hundreds of young people learn mathematics -- large numbers of them at the Hynes' kitchen table in the evening,&quot; Charles Dziuban, director of the UCF Research Initiative for Teaching Effectiveness, wrote in a nomination letter for Hynes. &quot;In </span>
<place></place>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Central Florida</span><span style="font-family: Arial">, it is common knowledge that the Hynes' kitchen table is always open for a math tutoring session.&quot;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Hynes, a UCF professor since 1971, accepted the Pegasus Professor Award, which recognizes outstanding teaching, research and service, during the annual Founders' Day ceremony on Wednesday. The award is the top honor that the university gives to a faculty member.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">Hynes holds the Lockheed Martin Eminent Scholar Chair for Mathematics in the </span>
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
<span style="font-family: Arial">College</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> of </span>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Education</span><span style="font-family: Arial">, and he is the director of the Lockheed Martin/UCF Academy for Mathematics and Science. He was associate dean for graduate studies and research from 1997 to 2004 and was assistant dean of the college from 1995 to 1997. </span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">Hynes' latest honor comes one year after the </span>
<place></place>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Lockheed</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Martin</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> </span>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Academy</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> for Mathematics and Science, which he founded, received the prestigious Christa McAuliffe Award from the American Association of State Colleges and Universities in 2004. That award recognizes outstanding programs in teacher education.</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">Hynes' prior awards at UCF include the University Researcher of the Year award in 1993 and the </span>
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
<span style="font-family: Arial">College</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> of </span>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Education</span><span style="font-family: Arial">Â’s Excellence in Research Award in 1982 and 1991 and Excellence in Teaching Award in 1985. </span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&quot;By his high intellect, insightful leadership, and dedicated service, Dr. Hynes has achieved unsurpassed personal and professional growth and success in academia,&quot; </span>
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
<span style="font-family: Arial">College</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> of </span>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Education Dean Sandra Robinson</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> wrote in a nomination letter. &quot;Throughout his progression, he has mentored generations of educators who, today, serve as the backbone of this university and the educational foundation of the </span>
<place></place>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Central Florida</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> region.&quot;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Robinson also praised Hynes for mentoring other professors and allowing them to participate in research projects with him so they can get the experience they need to lead their own research efforts later. </font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Hynes has helped to raise more than $3 million in gifts to the university during his career. That includes a $1 million gift from Martin Marietta, now Lockheed Martin, to start the Lockheed Martin/UCF Academy for Mathematics and Science. The state provided $753,000 in matching funds for the academy.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Hynes also helped to win a $270,000 award from the Toyota USA Foundation to start the Transition into Mathematics and Science Teaching program, a master's degree program that helps professionals become science and math teachers in middle schools.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">Pat Bishop, director of the Office of Graduate Studies, credited Hynes for the substantial increase in research funding at the </span>
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
<span style="font-family: Arial">College</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> of </span>
<placename></placename>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Education</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> and said he &quot;has sacrificed nights and weekends to make this come true.&quot;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Dan Crowley, president of Lockheed Martin Simulation, Training &amp; Support, praised Hynes' innovation and &quot;excellent stewardship&quot; of the academy.</font></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&quot;By enhancing the qualifications of mathematics and science teachers, Dr. Hynes has had a dramatic and ever-lasting effect on the lives of children throughout his community,&quot; </span><city></city>
<place></place>
<span style="font-family: Arial">Crowley</span><span style="font-family: Arial"> wrote.</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><font size="3"><span style="font-family: Arial">&nbsp;</span></font></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt"><span style="font-family: Arial"><font size="3">Hynes is the eighth winner of the Pegasus Professor Award, which was first awarded in 2000. Henry Daniell, a professor of molecular and microbiology, was the 2004 recipient. Winners receive a statue of the Pegasus, a Pegasus Professor Medallion and a check for $5,000.</font></span></p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

